If it makes anyone feel better, I haven't read more than a few pages of a book in a long time and I also feel guilty about it! Which ironically makes it even harder to get myself to read! Wow cool thanks, brain!
Also, I am the friend who promises to read books (fully intending to actually do so) and then never gets around to it.

I think most people probably don't think this deep about it when they keep putting it off, but it doesn't seem unlikely to me that all of that is there under the surface whether they realize it or not.

It's far easier to apologize for the mostly reasonable excuse of being too busy to read your friend's book, and far harder to do the work AND put yourself in a position where giving your honest opinion means hurting your friend who worked very hard for a long time on the thing.

You could have every intention of reading them in support of your accountant friend when you accept them, and then without an interest in reading tax documents, you just can't find the emotional energy to get through it & also give them your honest opinion on tax docs after.

This could be upsetting, but also what you write is going to appeal to a specific audience, and that might not be your friend.

To return to my original point, vampirism itself may not bring anyone back from the dead, but it is a catalyst for starting a new life and leaving an old one behind.
I have thought about this... a lot, and I have a lot more to say, but I've already swerved really hard away from where I started.

Unless they already had the capacity to be insensitive to guilt or to compromise on their morals, the change will, at most, deteriorate their impulse control enough to do bad things out of a chemical need for blood, and leave them riddled with remorse after the desire is sated.

That said, what sort of effect does it have on a person's personality when they regularly have to drink human blood, especially if they have to harvest the blood themselves?

The vampire instinct is to desire/enjoy drinking blood, but any resulting death is consequential.

But there's not a hormonal shift that fully amputates a person's morality (or at the very least, this is rare), so new vampires don't wake up as rabid little shit-goblins with a sadistic desire to kill unless that desire was already there.

These substantial changes to brain chemistry could induce the onset of some mental health conditions, and new hormonal imbalances could lead to an increase/decrease in things like irritability, libido, impulsivity, etc.

Overall, there are some minor physical changes, but primarily the vampire virus affects brain chemistry. In most ways, the person retains their human traits, but they will experience instinctive responses they likely didn't have before.

Vampirism is (literally) viral, aggressive, and assimilatory. Honestly, it works not unlike an mRNA vaccine because it's in there rewriting the person's DNA from human to vampire, and it has to do so cell-by-cell.

I've crafted the way vampirism works to be very "scientific" (because I'm tedious like that), while still retaining a few mystical properties.

In my universe, even biological processes count as "magic." But that's different from the type of magic that created vampirism.

Becoming a vampire doesn't ~*magically*~ give you a new personality—

—but trauma and highly emotional experiences can certainly change your mental/emotional trajectory.
The physical changes have the least bearing on this transformation of personality, which isn't even mystical, although the condition of being a vampire originates from a curse.

This "death" sounds metaphorical, and while that's not untrue, these characters do make hairpin turns onto new, unfamiliar paths from the moment they undergo the transformation process.

Whether they have asked for it or not, this is a literal point of no return. Drastic change.

Even though they don't experience an actual physical death, my vampire characters still experience the death of a previous version of themselves, punctuated by the moment they are turned vampire and caused by the unique, converging events leading up to that moment.

In my universe, vampires aren't undead, or particularly monster-like.

In fact, the human in transition can't die, or the transformation isn't possible (without a third-party magical input, at least).

When people are willing to part with their money for you? You're doing something right. Stop doubting yourself. Stop doing work for nothing.

You cannot be a full-time creator if you are not making a profit from the things you create.

You have to make money somehow. If you have people who are willing to pay you money, then make sure you're actually profiting from their investment! They want to support YOU. BECAUSE YOU PROVIDE THEM VALUE ALREADY. BECAUSE THEY FIND THE THING THEY ARE PAYING FOR VALUABLE.

The thing about those benefits is that they still lead to future profits so long as you're putting in the work to nurture the audience and community you've already amassed. If you're taking care of them, you're not taking advantage of them.

If you, as a creator, are going to do something for free, then make sure it's benefitting you to give it away for free. Doesn't have to mean financial benefit, but leverage that shit for gains of SOME kind.p
We have to stop viewing ourselves as audacious to ask for money for the work we do. We just have to.

Knowing what people are willing to spend their money on shows what people value and points to the ways you can serve your audience/community even more. They are telling you what they want with every purchase... And showing you the lack of value in the things they're not buying.

For creators, paid content has far more value than just the net profit. When a person spends money on a service or product you offer, they are literally investing in you. YOU. If you're the only person on your whole team, then this is especially true for you.

You can and SHOULD provide some value for free, but if you become the person who gives everything away for free, then you don't have an audience, you have a bunch of freeloaders masquerading as an audience.

You cannot please everyone.

You cannot be perfect.

But you can make money off of your hard work, so stop underselling yourself.

I have so many talented, creative friends who let their insecurities get in the way of their success. 

Let's just embrace that we are already putting ourselves out there and let it all land where it falls.

I talked to my grandma about this recently. She did a lot of cleaning for me as a kid. Perhaps because I'm her fave grandkid, but she said people always criticized her for it, that I wasn't going to learn how to clean if no one ever made me do it. 7/

But I'm glad that it stood out to her, because her memory of it helped me realize I had ADHD, and was an important clue to the affect ADHD had on me when I was a kid.

In the US, symptoms from childhood must be present for an ADHD diagnosis, but... lol what is memory. #ADHD 6/

I don't actually remember this incident that well, but my mom likes to tell this story even into my adulthood. It's a little embarrassing because even now, it highlights how much I feel BAD at cleaning and staying organized. 5/

Mom gave me a few hours to clean it while she was out of the house for something else, and in a panic, I called my grandma over to help.

When my mom got home, my grandma was cleaning my room, and I was sitting on my bed playing Pokemon on my Gameboy Color.  4/

I remember having the hardest time cleaning my room when I was a kid, not just that time, but any time, because I was so easily distracted by rediscovering things I hadn't seen in a while. 

Whatever it was, if it was interesting... I stopped cleaning to look at it. 3/
I was scared. I was SHOOK. She yelled at me for it, out of her frustration, and she almost never yelled for anything. I'd upset her and it was the worst feeling ever. 2/

My biggest overlooked sign of ADHD was when my mom discovered that I always "cleaned my room" by shoving all the stuff that was on the floor into the closet, because the sliding door came off the track. 1/

This isn't a call for anyone else to change themselves or their bios. I just think it's an interesting self-analysis.

and it's that part of me that learned to put myself first for once that shudders at the thought of identifying so strongly with either label ever again. 

Maybe I swung the pendulum too hard the other way, but I'll die on the hill that says "selfish isn't a dirty word."
I am a mom, and I have been a wife, but the time in my life where I felt those were the only two things I was, was the lowest time in my adult life,

there's something deep inside of me that just cringes so damn hard at what I think my subconscious recognizes as "overidentifying" with those things (even though I know very little about most people who have this in a twitter bio).

But recently I've realized that I have a discomfort just as much with when people refer to themselves in a way that puts their intimate (incl. familial) relationships first and foremost. 

It's fine to prioritize these people in your life, so I understand the inclination, but

I have always been extremely uncomfortable with terms that indicate a person belongs to someone else just because they're in a romantic relationship, and usually I think of this as "we belong to each other" or calling someone "my woman/man".

@goblinairy These may be different quantities of success, but I view them all as success, if your goal is to finish writing the story you love.

The only way to not meet that goal... is to let your vision of it in perfect form keep you from giving birth to it to begin with.

@goblinairy There are a few potential outcomes to doing NaNo:

1. You like what you got. Now you've got something to work with.
2. You don't like it, but now you've got something to work with.
3. It's trash. You delete it. And you now are armed with info on how to attack the idea next time.
@goblinairy That voice telling you to not do something because it might be painful to you is a good thing to have. There is a certain wisdom to choosing "the devil you know."

@goblinairy Nothing and no one is perfect. And just think of all the other things you've probably tried to do and on the first few tries... you weren't a pro at it. It's okay to put things down that aren't amazing. Sometimes it takes seeing it in bad form to make it better anyway.

This whole thread was accidental, but something I feel passionate about. I hope more people start trusting their kids enough to let them be responsible for their own success, whatever that means to that child.

Feel free to ask me if you have any questions about Sudbury schools.

My kid is smart and adaptable. He will learn what he needs to if/when he needs to, and I have full faith in that. Previous students of these schools (called Sudbury schools), have gone on to prove academic success in college, 

but also that success is what they define it as.

Why do kids have to know any particular information/skill at any age? For the most part, the answer is curriculum designed for a different era.

When we trust our kids to be responsible for their own success, they find reasons to learn the things that "everyone should know."

For me, even if he didn't manage to learn a single thing ever again, that outcome is worth all of it.

But there are things he probably just won't teach himself that most kids his age should know...right?

He gets to be himself, interact with a variety of people, talk endlessly about his passion for military history, and best of all, I don't feel like I'm torturing him by sending him to school every day.

At his new school, he's more often than not *excited* to go. He can wear whatever he wants, and he takes full advantage of that by frequently wearing hats (which he collects) or costumes which often are related to whichever historical period he is currently fascinated with.

In public school, my child's ADHD helped create and exacerbate problems with his self-esteem, and I sent him off to school every day in fourth grade groaning, sometimes crying. Because he knew he was going to feel bad at school.

The most heartbreaking experience of my life.

Have you considered, however, that play is learning too? When we interact with others, we learn from each other, we learn from natural consequences, we learn vital skills that can't be learned from behind a desk with 20 other resentfully quiet kids who don't want to be there.

So why can't education include a person's ability to socialize? To have total control over what their school day is like and to figure out how to utilize that power to their maximum benefit? 

It's true, a lot of the kids at my son's school just play all day long.

And sure, some schools teach those helpful life things. In public school, my kid learned about stocks, but he can't remember much more than that about it. So once again, we are back to traditional schooling and its one-size-fits-all approach being more obstacle than benefit.

That's the fundamental difference here, despite all the other ways that self-directed education and traditional schooling lack resemblance. 

You think education means STEM or even arts. But that omits every subject you wish you'd learned in school now that you're an adult.

How can he possibly learn anything if he gets to go to school and do literally whatever he wants all day? 

The answer requires you to take a step back and reflect on your own beliefs and biases about education and then challenge them.

What does it mean to learn?
You're probably a little worried now that he's not learning anything while he's at school. That's an understandable fear, and definitely an objection I raised (to myself) when considering the school.

The school is entirely age-mixed. There aren't grade levels. There's no homework. No tests. There's not even a curriculum. There's no "teachers." It looks almost nothing like traditional schooling (and traditional schooling looks suspiciously like prison).

So I put my son in a school where his education is 100% self-directed. The school provides multitudes of resources, a budget, and staff members who are there to facilitate any educational whim the students have, provided they can approve use of funds democratically.

This goes for mostly everyone else as well, of course. Finding your subject matter enjoyable positively affects your overall ability to retain the information. Similar effect if you have motivation to learn apart from "the state says so."

Desire is powerful.

Learning really does take an invested interest for anything to remain long-term. As people with ADHD, my son and I experience this to the extreme. We're quick learners when we need to be, but we're engaged learners when we're passionate about what we're learning.

It's not easy to just do that, of course. I don't want to see him get hurt, or feel uncomfortable or uneasy, ever. I find myself giving lectures to hazed over eyes where I try to impart my experiences with words, but I can feel my advice sliding right off his brain. It's natural.
"Don't touch that, it's hot" is only fractionally as impactful as experiencing getting burnt, and eventually we all have that experience no matter how many times we hear the warnings.
I do my best to allow my child all the autonomy I can because I believe if you want your kid to be independent, then you have to trust them to be that. So much in life is learned through consequence.

Every day, reflection
in the morning, in the mirror.
Do I wash my face? Do I scrub it clean?
Do I rebuild it, embrace yesterday's makeup,
make up a story
to convince myself I love the face
I make when I realize
my everyday reflection is a reflection
of every day of my life?

We reach our grasping hands
across the chasm between us
to hold on in spite of it all.
In spite of second thoughts.
In spite of the fact that holding on
to your hand demotes us each
from protagonist
to secondary comic relief
in a sci-fi horror where we travel time,
but not space.

topple the fragile structure to the ground,
and leave you among the broken fragments,
thanking me for sparing
the ones you couldn't live without. #amwriting #poetry

Your brain is seeking dopamine AT ALL TIMES. It is VERY GOOD at putting activities into 2 categories:

"Rewarding" (aka: gives dopamine)

or

"Never Do This Not in A Million Years" (aka: no dopamine😥)

These are the only categories.

If you've been waiting for a good reason to reach out to someone you love, consider this it.

Do it right now.

You don't have to have anything to say. It's not about the words. It's the connection. Tell them you're thinking about them. Ask how they are. Just do it.

I'm not good at affection. It doesn't come naturally to me, and I'm a bit touch averse, so the obvious methods of giving affection are mostly out of the question. 

But as a reminder to myself: it doesn't take much to show someone you care. You're awkward, not heartless.

I don't think selfishness is innately bad; we have to protect ourselves. But let's not ignore the harm we cause sometimes in serving our wants over others' needs.

And let's not cause ourselves any more regret by ignoring the phone when we think of someone we should talk to.
And how there's no way to make a single person act on their responsibility to the rest of us, especially if they aren't capable of the emotional maturity it takes to do so.
I'm thinking about how much power we hold in every decision we make, how there are decisions that could save lives, nurture relationships, that could change the world for one of us, or all of us.

But today, I'm thinking about loss
of family 
of friends
of memories that could have been.

The rest of us too, sure—but she's the one robbed of memories she and her brother could have made. 

It's a bit of a stretch to blame society for my grief today, maybe.

Probably.

And it's absolutely enraging that she's done her part to end this pandemic, pulled more weight than most of us, has been beyond cautious, and still there are too many people out there who never took up their responsibility to her.

But the idea that my friend is suffering, that she might blame herself for not visiting sooner, that she feels the weight of her mother's depression and the complicating effect finding her son dead at home will add to that.

I'm crying for her. She doesn't deserve this.

I definitely need to do more phone calling with my loved ones. To be honest, there's very little loss I feel personally at this moment. He wasn't my brother to lose. I wonder if it means I'm heartless, or calloused, or perhaps just in denial.

I'm thinking about how when a friend comes to me with a problem, I want to provide a solution, some sort of relief, and how that's not always possible and how that might not even be why they came to me. I'm wondering if I need to do more listening.

I let her decide to switch topics, and then I was happy to provide a distraction by catching her up on what had happened with me recently. A conversation we normally would have had a few months ago, but that COVID took from us this time around.

I don't know that anyone knows what to say on that phone call, but I know that I didn't. I admitted as much. She did the same. What is there to say after sorry? I remember thinking I was the wrong person to call for comfort.

It's been even longer for me since I've seen her brother. Until she said his name on the phone, I had more or less forgotten he existed. My memories of him are of him being the obnoxious younger brother at sleepovers, and a few glimpses of his face as an adult.

When she called me yesterday, I knew something was wrong. She's one of my best friends, but we don't call each other. That's not our thing. We see each other at the holidays (my birthday, usually), and we catch up on everything since the last time we saw each other a year before.

Because of the pandemic, and living in different states, she hasn't seen him since 2019. She was going to come back here to visit for his birthday in two months. She thought he would be vaccinated by then.

But he won't be here.

cw// death, loss, covid

Today, I'm thinking about loss. I'm wondering about grief. A friend I consider one of my best, but who I hardly talk to because of distance, lost her younger brother yesterday.

Note about email freebies:

If you don't have short stories to send out, consider a first chapter (or 2 or 3) for free. Something that will get your audience invested without requiring a purchase. Honestly if you're selling books, the chapter freebie might be the way to go.

Note about value:

If you're an author, the value you provide is the emotional impact of your writing. People buy products because it meets an EMOTIONAL/PSYCHOLOGICAL NEED for them. Entertainment is a need. Your audience = the person looking to feel the emotions your book evokes.

+ your subscribers will stay subscribed and the people who aren't right for your brand will unsubscribe. It's okay for them to leave if they don't like it. It only distills your audience down to its most devoted and satisfied members. They'll have the most valuable feedback too!

But please stop calling it a "newsletter." It's only hurting you, and you hate writing newsletter emails anyway. Treat your email subscribers like people you're talking to directly—because that's what you're doing! As long as you are providing *VALUE* that suits your brand, +

Nobody wants to read your newsletter. But they WILL read your free short story after giving you their email address for it. As long as you are upfront about your intentions with your email list, it's okay to give people something of value for the chance to talk to them directly.
